<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1739,2016]" pageId="5" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1739,1764]" pageId="5" pageNumber="62">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mederos" authorityYear="2018" box="[281,467,1739,1764]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" genus="Keroplatus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maxi">
<emphasis box="[281,467,1739,1764]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="62">Keroplatus maxi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all the other Neotropical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bosc" authorityYear="1792" box="[1063,1187,1739,1764]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" genus="Keroplatus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1063,1187,1739,1764]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="62">Keroplatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the overall yellow colour of the body with almost no markings, eXcept for the particular pattern of stripes on the dorsal part of thoraX; the wings with a slight pale yellowish tint and a total absence of coloured spots, and finally by the unique shape of the genitalia, particularly the gonostylus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
